<subSubSection id="C37AA3E2FFD4AD071BCB48AE02149669" pageId="12" pageNumber="503" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BDFF069FFD4AD071BCB48AE02149669" blockId="12.[151,1437,258,1543]" pageId="12" pageNumber="503">
<emphasis id="B9142C7BFFD4AD071BCB48AE025B958C" bold="true" box="[199,334,1482,1507]" pageId="12" pageNumber="503">Etymology.</emphasis>
This epithet is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis id="B9142C7BFFD4AD07180D48AE0043958C" box="[769,854,1482,1507]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="503">grandis</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B9142C7BFFD4AD07188148AE00F5958C" box="[909,992,1482,1507]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="503">lobatus</emphasis>
, referring to the large lobate process of the costa.
</paragraph>
